<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-func-transformations" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Transformations of Functions</title>

  <definition>
    <title>transformation</title>

    <statement>
      <p>
        <alert>Transformations</alert> are rule-based <em>changes</em> to the graph of a function. Each transformation can occur in one of two directions: <em>vertical</em> or <em>horizontal</em>. There are three types of transformations:
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>Translation</em>- This represents a change in <em>location</em>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <em>Dilation</em>- This represents a change in <em>size</em>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <em>Reflection</em>- This represents a change in <em>orientation</em>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <p>
    Given a function <m>f(x)</m>, a transformation of <m>f(x)</m> is a function of the form
  </p>

  <tabular>
    <row>
      <cell> </cell>
    </row>

    <row>
      <cell> <alert> <m>\mathbf{a}</m>: vertical dilation and/or reflection</alert> </cell>
      <cell>negative: reflect over <m>x</m>-axis</cell>
    </row>

    <row>
      <cell> </cell>
      <cell> <m>\mathbf{|a|}>1</m> taller    <m>\mathbf{|a|}&#x3C;1</m> shorter</cell>
    </row>

    <row>
      <cell> </cell>
    </row>

    <row>
      <cell> <alert> <m>\mathbf{b}</m>: horizontal dilation and/or reflection</alert> </cell>
      <cell>negative: reflect over <m>y</m>-axis</cell>
    </row>

    <row>
      <cell> </cell>
      <cell> <m>\mathbf{|b|}>1</m> narrower    <m>\mathbf{|b|}&#x3C;1</m> wider</cell>
    </row>

    <row>
      <cell> </cell>
    </row>

    <row>
      <cell> <alert> <m>\mathbf{c}</m>: horizontal translation</alert> </cell>
      <cell> <m>\mathbf{c}</m> positive (subtraction from <m>x</m>): right</cell>
    </row>

    <row>
      <cell> </cell>
      <cell> <m>\mathbf{c}</m> negative (addition to x): left</cell>
    </row>

    <row>
      <cell> </cell>
    </row>

    <row>
      <cell> <alert> <m>\mathbf{d}</m>: vertical translation</alert> </cell>
      <cell> <m>\mathbf{d}</m> positive: up</cell>
    </row>

    <row>
      <cell> </cell>
      <cell> <m>\mathbf{d}</m> negative: down</cell>
    </row>

    <row>
      <cell> </cell>
    </row>
  </tabular>

  <p>
    Note: Follow the order of operations to perform multiple transformations in sequence: <m>\mathbf{c}</m>, then <m>\mathbf{b}</m>, then <m>\mathbf{a}</m>, then <m>\mathbf{d}</m>.
  </p>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        <em>(Transforming Points)</em>Describe the sequence of transformations of the graph of <m>f(x)=x^{2}</m> to obtain the graph of <m>g(x)=-3(x+2)^{2} -1</m>, then sketch <m>g(x)</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        <em>(Transforming Features)</em>Describe the sequence of transformations of the graph of <m>f(x)=|x|</m> to obtain the graph of <m>g(x)=-3|x+2|-1</m>, then sketch <m>g(x)</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>
</section>